The '''Coleman Frog''' is a {{convert|19|kg|lb}} [[taxidermy]] [[frog]] on display at the [[Fredericton Region Museum]] in [[Fredericton]], [[New Brunswick]]. It was previously owned by a man named Fred Coleman, who ran a nearby lodge in the 1880s. The frog was captured from [[Lake Killarney (Missouri)|Killarney Lake]], at which time it weighed {{convert|7.3|lb|kg}}.<ref name="york" /><ref name="lewiston">{{cite news | url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1928&dat=19790412&id=DGEgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=wmUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1439,2039525&hl=en | title=Story of famous "Coleman Frog" | work=The Lewiston Daily Sun | date=Apr 12, 1979 | agency=Christian Science Monitor | accessdate=May 16, 2015 | pages=7}}</ref> Supposedly, the immense size of the frog was caused by the fact that Coleman fed it whiskey and [[whey]]. It died in a "dynamite accident" and was sent to [[Bangor, Maine]] to be stuffed.<ref name="york">{{cite web | url=https://yorksunburymuseum.wordpress.com/2009/06/24/the-coleman-frog/ | title=The Coleman Frog | publisher=York Sunbury Museum | date=June 24, 2009 | accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref> [[Skeptic]]s say that the frog is a fake that was used to promote a cough syrup that would "relieve the frog in your throat".<ref name="hoaxes">{{cite web | url=http://hoaxes.org/weblog/comments/coleman_frog | title=The Coleman Frog | publisher=Museum of Hoaxes | date=July 30, 2007 | accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref> The Museum will not allow DNA testing to be done on the frog to confirm if it is real or fake.<ref name="hoaxes" /><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.canada.com/story.html?id=3327c432-bbd3-4710-9da1-26bb69b749e3 | title=Monster frog no bull, says museum manager | work=Canada.com | date=July 28, 2007 | agency=Canwest News Service | accessdate=May 16, 2015}}</ref>
