{{short description|A-class submarine of the Royal Navy }} {{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}} {{Use British English|date=February 2018}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image |Ship image=HMS A3.jpg |Ship caption=HMS ''A3'' }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header= |Ship country=United Kingdom |Ship flag={{shipboxflag|UK|naval}} |Ship name=HMS ''A3'' |Ship ordered= |Ship awarded= |Ship builder=[[Vickers#Vickers.2C Sons .26 Maxim|Vickers, Sons & Maxim Ltd.]] [[Barrow-in-Furness]], [[England]] |Ship original cost= |Ship yard number= |Ship way number= |Ship laid down=6 November 1902 |Ship launched=9 March 1903 |Ship sponsor= |Ship christened= |Ship completed= |Ship commissioned=13 July 1904 |Ship recommissioned= |Ship decommissioned= |Ship maiden voyage= |Ship in service= |Ship out of service= |Ship renamed= |Ship refit= |Ship struck= |Ship homeport= |Ship motto= |Ship nickname= |Ship honours= |Ship fate=Sunk, 12 May 1912 |Ship status= |Ship notes= |Ship badge= }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header= |Header caption= |Ship class={{sclass2-|A|submarine (1903)|0}} [[submarine]] |Ship displacement=*{{convert|190|LT|t|0|abbr=on}} surfaced *{{convert|206|LT|t|0|abbr=on}} submerged |Ship length={{convert|105|ft|m|abbr=on|1}} |Ship beam={{convert|12|ft|9|in|m|abbr=on|1}} |Ship height= |Ship draught={{convert|10|ft|8|in|m|abbr=on|1}} |Ship depth= |Ship power=*{{convert|450|bhp|lk=in|abbr=on}} ([[petrol engine]]) *{{convert|150|hp|abbr=on}} ([[electric motor]]) |Ship propulsion=*1 × 16-cylinder Wolseley petrol engine *1 × electric motor |Ship speed=*{{convert|10|kn|lk=in}} surfaced *{{convert|7|kn}} submerged |Ship range={{convert|320|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|10|kn|abbr=on}} surfaced |Ship test depth= |Ship complement=2 officers and 9 ratings |Ship armament=2 × [[British 18 inch torpedo|18-inch (45&nbsp;cm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s }} |}
'''HMS ''A3''''' was an {{sclass2-|A|submarine (1903)|0}} [[submarine]] built for the [[Royal Navy]] in the first decade of the 20th century.
==Design and description== ''A3'' was a member of the [[A-class submarine (1903)|first British class of submarines]], although slightly larger, faster and more heavily armed than the [[lead ship]], {{HMS|A1}}. The submarine had a length of {{convert|105|ft|1|in|m|1}} [[length overall|overall]], a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|12|ft|9|in|m|1}} and a mean [[draft (ship)|draft]] of {{convert|10|ft|8|in|m|1}}. They [[displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{convert|190|LT|t}} on the surface and {{convert|206|LT|t}} submerged. The A-class submarines had a crew of 2 officers and 11 [[other ranks (UK)|ratings]].<ref name=gg9>Gardiner & Gray, p. 86</ref>
For surface running, the boats were powered by a single 16-cylinder {{convert|450|bhp|lk=in|0|adj=on}} [[Wolseley Motors|Wolseley]] [[petrol engine]] that drove one [[propeller shaft]]. When submerged the propeller was driven by a {{convert|150|hp|0|adj=on}} [[electric motor]]. They could reach {{convert|10|kn|lk=in}} on the surface and {{convert|7|kn}} underwater. On the surface, ''A3'' had a range of {{convert|320|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|10|kn}};<ref name=gg9/> submerged the boat had a range of {{convert|30|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|5|kn}}.<ref>Akermann, p. 120</ref>
The boats were armed with two [[British 18 inch torpedo|18-inch (45&nbsp;cm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s in the bow. They could carry a pair of reload torpedoes, but generally did not as doing so that they had to compensate for their weight by an equivalent weight of fuel.<ref>Harrison, Chapter 27</ref>
==Construction and career== ''A3'' was built at [[Vickers]], [[Barrow-in-Furness]] and was commissioned on 13 July 1904. She was accidentally rammed while surfacing by the [[submarine tender]] {{HMS|Hazard|1894|2}} in the [[English Channel]] off the [[Isle of Wight]] on 2 February 1912 and sank with the loss of all on board.<ref>*{{cite book|author=Innes McCartney|title=Lost Patrols: Submarine Wrecks of the English Channel|year=2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Disasters of the Deep A Comprehensive Survey of Submarine Accidents & Disasters |last=Gray |first=Edwyn |authorlink=Edwyn Gray |year=2003|publisher=Leo Cooper|isbn=0-85052-987-5 |pages=69–70}}</ref> The wreck was salvaged and subsequently sunk as a gunnery target in the English Channel near [[Isle of Portland|Portland Bill]] on 12 May 1912, where she remains today. In July 2016 the wreck of ''A3'' was officially designated as a protected site.<ref>{{cite news|title=British A3 submarine sunk off Jurassic Coast in 1912 gets protected status|url=http://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/14636155.British_submarine_sunk_off_Jurassic_Coast_gets_protected_status/|accessdate=24 July 2016|work=Dorset Echo|publisher=Newsquest Media|date=22 July 2016}}</ref>
