{{chart bottom}}

Haraldr also ruled during a period of competing claims to the overlordship of the Isles,<ref name="Stringer 2004">[[#S6|Stringer (2004)]]; [[#H2|Helle (2009)]].</ref> a region comprising the [[Hebrides]] and [[Isle of Man|Mann]], known in the Norse world as ''{{lang|non|Suðreyjar}}'' (the "Southern Islands") due to its geographical position in relation to [[Norway]] itself.<ref>[[#G2|Grohse (2013)]] pp. 257 fig. 1, 258; [[#M13|McDonald (2012)]] p. 152.</ref> Since the reign of [[Magnús berfœttr, King of Norway]], a king who conquered [[Earldom of Orkney|Orkney]], the Isles, and possibly [[Kingdom of Dublin|Dublin]] before his death in 1103, the [[King of Norway|Norwegian Crown]] appears to have claimed ultimate authority in the Isles.<ref>[[#B2|Beuermann (2010)]] p. 105.</ref> In fact, on several occasions during the reigns of Haraldr's royal predecessors, leading Islesmen sought recognition and protection from Norwegian monarchs.<ref>[[#B2|Beuermann (2010)]] pp. 106&ndash;108.</ref> The ruler of Norway during Haraldr's [[floruit]] was [[Hákon Hákonarson, King of Norway]], a formidable ruler who spent the latter part of his reign focused on foreign policy and strengthening royal authority throughout far-flung Norse colonies such as the Isles.<ref>[[#H2|Helle (2009)]].</ref> At the same time the [[King of Scotland|Scottish Crown]], in the person of [[Alexander II, King of Scotland]], consolidated control over Scotland's western seaboard, and moved to extend Scottish influence further into the Isles.<ref name="Stringer 2004"/> Meanwhile, [[Henry III, King of England]] also had an interest in the Isles, and worked to bring the Crovan dynasty closer under the orbit of the [[King of England|English Crown]].<ref name="Barrow 1981 p. 111">[[#B4|Barrow (1981)]] p. 111.</ref>

==Accession and overlordship==

{{multiple image
| footer    = [[Manx runestones#Hedin Cross|Maughold IV]] (image a), a [[Manx runestone]] displaying a contemporary sailing vessel (detail, image b).<ref name="combine1">[[#M13|McDonald (2012)]] p. 151; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 55, 128&ndash;129 pl. 1; [[#W4|Wilson (1973)]] p. 15.</ref> The power of the [[kings of the Isles]] laid in their armed galley-fleets.<ref>[[#M13|McDonald (2012)]] p. 151; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 128&ndash;129 pl. 1.</ref>{{#tag:ref|The inscription of the vessel may date to about the time of the Crovan dynasty, possibly from about the eleventh- to the thirteenth century.<ref name="combine1"/> The vessel itself appears to be similar to those that appear on seals borne by members of the dynasty.<ref>[[#M7|McDonald (2007a)]] pp. 58&ndash;60; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 54&ndash;55; [[#W4|Wilson (1973)]] p. 15, 15 n. 43.</ref>|group=note}}
| align     = left
| image1    = Hedin's cross.jpg
| width1    = {{#expr: (170 * 374 / 472 ) round 0}}
| caption1  = {{center|Image a}}
| alt1      = Illustration of Maughold IV, a Manx runetstone
| image2    = Maughold stone, Hedin cross, ship.jpg
| width2    = {{#expr: (170 * 380 / 494) round 0}}
| caption2  = {{center|Image b}}
| alt2      = Illustration of an inscribed sailing vessel on Maughold IV
