After his father's death, Haraldr succeeded to the kingship.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 87, 106, 171; [[#P8|Power (2005)]] p. 46; [[#D8|Duffy (1993)]] p. 107.</ref> Unlike the reign of his father, who temporarily ruled a partitioned kingdom, and endured years of near catastrophic kin-strife, Haraldr appears to have ruled a whole kingdom, and his kingship does not seem to have suffered from serious dynastic discord.<ref name="McDonald pp. 87, 90"/> Haraldr's young age at the time of his accession, and the fact that he had a potential rival in the person of Haraldr Guðrøðarson, suggests that Haraldr had been designated successor during his father's lifetime.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 171&ndash;172.</ref> Not long after his accession, the ''Chronicle of Mann'' records that he sailed into the Hebridean portion of the kingdom, and left a kinsman named Lochlann as governor on Mann. Lochlann's tenure on the island led to factional strife, and when Haraldr made his return the following spring, the chronicle states that Lochlann fled the island for [[Wales]], taking with him his [[foster-son]], Guðrøðr Óláfsson. There, somewhere along the northern Welsh coast, the chronicle claims that their ship was lost, with Lochlann and his foster-son amongst the dead.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#M6|Moore (2013)]] ch. 3; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 52, 106; [[#S2|Smith (1998)]] p. 38 n. 5; [[#W5|Williams (1997)]] p. 260 n. 117; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 507&ndash;509; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 94&ndash;97.</ref> Quite why Lochlann was compelled to flee his sovereign in uncertain. The chronicle states that a friend of Haraldr had been slain in the uprising quelled by Lochlann, possibly indicate that the latter fled in fear of the king. Another possibility, is that Lochlann led a coalition opposed to Haraldr.<ref>[[#W5|Williams (1997)]] p. 260 n. 117.</ref> Quite why Lochlann chose to Wales as his destination is also unknown,<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 106.</ref> although the Crovan dynasty certainly had diplomatic and familial connections with the Welsh.<ref>[[#M6|Moore (2013)]] ch. 3; [[#M7|McDonald (2007a)]] p. 55; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 106.</ref> In fact, a transaction between [[Llywelyn ap Gruffudd]] and [[Ralph de Mortimer]] that concerns the lands of [[Maelienydd]] and [[Gwerthrynion]], and appears to date to 1241, makes note of a witness named "''{{lang|la|Godredo filio regis Mannie}}''".<ref>[[#M6|Moore (2013)]] ch. 3; [[#M7|McDonald (2007a)]] pp. 55&ndash;56 n. 49; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 106; [[#P1|Pryce; Insley (2005)]] p. 490 (§ 317); [[#S2|Smith (1998)]] p. 38, 38 n. 5.</ref> The precise identity of this man is uncertain.<ref name="M4-106107">[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 106&ndash;107.</ref> One possibility is that he is identical to Lochlann's foster-son.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 106&ndash;107; [[#S2|Smith (1998)]] p. 38, 38 n. 5.</ref> If the chronicle is in error in its account of the maritime demise of Guðrøðr Óláfsson, and he is indeed  identical to the like-named Manx prince on record in Wales, his activities outwith the kingdom of his forefathers may have been a consequence of the troubles following the Haraldr's accession.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 106&ndash;107; [[#S2|Smith (1998)]] p. 38, 38 n. 5.</ref> The chronicle's account of the flight to Wales may, therefore, reveal that Lochlann tried and failed to replace Haraldr with an otherwise unknown younger son of Óláfr. If so, the episode would appear to be yet another example of the Crovan dynasty enduring internal strife.<ref name="O4">[[#O4|Oram (2013)]].</ref>

[[File:Tynwald tingvollen.jpg|alt=Photo of Tynwald Hill|thumb|[[Tynwald Hill]], near [[St John's, Isle of Man|St John's]] may have been a national [[Thing (assembly)|assembly site]] of the Kingdom of the Isles.<ref name="B5">[[#B5|Broderick (2003)]].</ref> It may well have been the place where the Islesmen publicly inaugurated their kings,<ref>[[#C4|Crawford (2014)]] pp. 74&ndash;75.</ref> proclaimed new laws, and resolved disputes.<ref name="I1">[[#I1|Insley; Wilson (2006)]].</ref> Be that as it may, much of the visible site dates only to the eighteenth-, nineteenth-, and twentieth century.<ref name="B5"/>{{#tag:ref|Evidence of local assembly sites within the kingdom may exist in the Hebridean placenames ''Tiongal'' (known in [[Scottish Gaelic]] as ''{{lang|gd|Cnoc an Tiongalairidh}}'') on [[Isle of Lewis|Lewis]] ({{gbmapping|NB1937}}),<ref>[[#O7|O'Grady (2008)]] p. 203, 599 tab 4.8; [[#I1|Insley; Wilson (2006)]]; [[#B5|Broderick (2003)]].</ref> and ''Tinwhil'' (perhaps {{gbmapping|NG415583}}) within the ''Hinnisdale'' area on [[Skye]].<ref>[[#O7|O'Grady (2008)]] pp. 201&ndash;203, 597 tab. 4.8; [[#B5|Broderick (2003)]].</ref> Like the Manx site, these four Hebridean placenames are derived in part from the Old Norse ''{{lang|non|þing}}'' ("assembly").<ref>[[#O7|O'Grady (2008)]] pp. 56&ndash;61, 201&ndash;203, 597 tab. 4.8, 599 tab 4.8; [[#B5|Broderick (2003)]].</ref> These sites, and others now lost, may have been established before the dominance of Manx-based kings and their national assembly site.<ref>[[#O7|O'Grady (2008)]] p. 194.</ref> Although the Manx site is first noted by the ''Chronicle of Mann'', the form of name (''"{{lang|la|tyngualla}}"'' and ''"{{lang|la|tingualla}}"'') suggests that it is quite old, perhaps dating to the ninth century.<ref>[[#I1|Insley; Wilson (2006)]]; [[#B5|Broderick (2003)]]; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 92, 94.</ref> The hill is the site of the island's modern national assembly, [[Tynwald]], held annually on [[Old Midsummer's Day]].<ref name="I1"/>|group=note}}]]

Later in 1238, the chronicle reveals that envoys of Hákon expelled Haraldr from Mann because the latter had refused to render [[Homage (feudal)|homage]] to his overlord in Norway. Hákon's delegates in the Isles&mdash;a certain Gospatric, and Giolla Críost mac Muircheartaigh&mdash;are described by the chronicle to have seized control of the island, and taken tribute which was due to the Norwegian king.<ref>[[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] p. 51; [[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#B2|Beuermann (2010)]] pp. 107, 108 n. 28; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 87, 151; [[#B3|Brown (2004)]] pp. 79&ndash;80; [[#W5|Williams (1997)]] p. 260; [[#B4|Barrow (1981)]] p. 111; [[#J2|Johnsen (1969)]] pp. 26&ndash;27, 26 n. 8; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] p. 512; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 96&ndash;97.</ref> By sending such emissaries&mdash;men apparently without any hereditary claim to the kingdom&mdash;Hákon ignored other potential claimants, such as other members of the Crovan dynasty and members of Clann Somhairle.<ref>[[#B2|Beuermann (2010)]] pp. 107, 108 n. 28.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Less than a decade before, Hákon had demonstrated Norwegian overlordship in a similar fashion by conferring kingship upon [[Óspakr-Hákon]] whilst ignoring other claimants. With the latter's untimely death not long afterwards, Hákon seems to have been responsible for the partitioning of the Crovan dynasty's domain between Óláfr, and Guðrøðr Dond, Óláfr's nephew.<ref>[[#B2|Beuermann (2010)]] p. 107, 107 n. 25.</ref>|group=note}} About a decade before, when Haraldr's father first gained complete control of the kingdom, Óláfr journeyed to Norway and may have rendered homage to Hákon.<ref>[[#M1|McNamee (2005)]]; [[#J2|Johnsen (1969)]] p. 26.</ref> Later in 1235 Óláfr rendered homage to Henry,<ref>[[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] p. 51; [[#M6|Moore (2013)]] ch. 3; [[#M1|McNamee (2005)]].</ref> before being called back to Norway the following year.<ref>[[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] p. 51; [[#M1|McNamee (2005)]].</ref> The episode concerning the ejection of Haraldr may well be related to his father's fealty to the English Crown,<ref>[[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] p. 51.</ref> and appears to indicate that the latter was deposed for not fulfilling his duties as a Norwegian [[vassal]]; and that upon his subsequent removal, Haraldr's rights of vassalage passed to Hákon himself.<ref>[[#J2|Johnsen (1969)]] p. 27.</ref>

Although Haraldr attempted to oust Hákon's representatives on several occasions, his successive invasions of Mann from the Hebrides ultimately proved unsuccessful, and the chronicle indicates that he finally journeyed to Norway to render his submission. After a stay of about two or three years in Scandinavia, the chronicle reports that Haraldr became reconciled with Hákon, who restored him to the kingship. The source reveals that the boundaries of his kingdom were carefully defined by Hákon as the islands which had been previously ruled by Haraldr's father, his uncle (Rǫgnvaldr Guðrøðarson), and his paternal grandfather.<ref>[[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] p. 51; [[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#B2|Beuermann (2010)]] pp. 107&ndash;108; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 87, 151; [[#B3|Brown (2004)]] pp. 79&ndash;80; [[#J2|Johnsen (1969)]] p. 27, 27 n. 1; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] p. 512; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 96&ndash;99.</ref> The Norwegian king, therefore, not only deliberately excluded the island territories ruled by Clann Somhairle, but limited the possibility of Haraldr becoming in drawn into alignment with Scottish interests like some leading members of Clann Somhairle had been.<ref name="O4"/> Upon his return to the Isles, the chronicle states that the Manxmen rejoiced at his arrival; and declares that he afterwards reigned quietly and peacefully, enjoying an alliance of friendship with both the English and Scottish Crowns.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#W5|Williams (1997)]] p. 260; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] p. 533; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 98&ndash;99.</ref>

==Acta and honours==

[[File:Harald Olafsson, King of Mann and the Isles (seal 03).png|alt=Illustration of a mediaeval charter and seal|thumb|upright|left|Seventeenth-century illustration of a [[royal charter|charter]] and [[Seal (emblem)|seal]] of Haraldr.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 128&ndash;129 fig. 2.</ref>]]

The earliest member of the Crovan dynasty known to have utilised a [[Seal (emblem)|seal]] is Haraldr's paternal grandfather, who attached such a device to a confirmation charter granted in about 1154.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 204; [[#O2|Oliver (1861)]] pp. 13&ndash;14.</ref> Although none of the original seals borne by the Crovan dynasty have survived, several were documented by sixteenth- and seventeenth-century [[antiquarian]]s. In regards to Haraldr himself, one such antiquarian named [[Christopher Hatton, 1st Baron Hatton|Christopher Hatton]] not only transcribed two of Haraldr's charters, but made drawings of the seals which were attached to them. The devices themselves were in poor condition by Hatton's time, as his illustrations show portions of them broken away. It is clear, however, that the seals bore a lion on one side, and a [[clinker-built]] galley with sails furled on the other side.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 55&ndash;56, 204&ndash;205; [[#R3|Rixson (1982)]] pp. 127&ndash;128.</ref> About a century later, the charters and seals, along with other priceless documents of the [[Cottonian Library]], were destroyed by fire at [[Ashburnham House]] in 1731.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 55&ndash;56, 162, 204&ndash;205; [[#C5|''Cotton Manuscripts'' (n.d.)]] p. 39.</ref> Waxen seals affixed to acta not only served to authenticate the written documents, but also physically symbolise the authority and significance of them.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 204.</ref> For example, when Hákon formally confirmed the kingship of [[Magnús Óláfsson, King of Mann and the Isles]], Haraldr's younger brother and eventual royal successor, the Norwegian king is said by the ''Chronicle of Mann'' to have done so "by the protection of his seal".<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 99, 152; [[#R3|Rixson (1982)]] p. 127; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] p. 578; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 108&ndash;109.</ref> To the kings of the Crovan dynasty, whose military strength laid in the power of armed galley-fleets, the symbol of such a vessel upon their seals represented the strength and authority they held in the Isles.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 204&ndash;206; [[#R3|Rixson (1982)]] p. 127.</ref>

{{multiple image
| footer    = Existing remains of two Manx churches recorded in acta dating to Haraldr's reign. The church of St Runius was drastically altered in the eighteenth century. The church of St Ninian is largely a fourteenth-century ruin.<ref>[[#M8|Megaw (1950)]] pp. 180&ndash;182.</ref>
| align     = right
| image1    = Marown Old Church - geograph.org.uk - 3125.jpg
| caption1  = {{center|Marown Old Church (the church of St Runius)}}
| width1    = {{#expr: (120 * 640 / 480) round 0}}
| alt1      = Photograh of Marown Old Church
| image2    = The medieval chapel of St. Trinian's, near Crosby - geograph.org.uk - 58337.jpg
| caption2  = {{center|St Trinian's Chapel (the church of [[St Ninian]])}}
| width2    = {{#expr: (120 * 640 / 480) round 0}}
| alt2      = Photograh of St Trinian's Chapel
}}

One of Haraldr's charters to which a seal was attached was a grant to the monks of [[Furness Abbey]] concerning mining rights on Mann, the use of a depot at "''{{lang|la|Bakenaldwath}}''" (probably [[Ronaldsway]]), and the freedom from tolls and customs.<ref>[[#M2|McDonald (2015)]]; [[#M7|McDonald (2007a)]] p. 49; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 45, 193, 195, 219; [[#O2|Oliver (1861)]] pp. 79&ndash;81; [[#P2|''PoMS, H1/17/3'' (n.d.)]].</ref> The record of this document is the earliest evidence for mineral exploitation on the island, an industry that expanded throughout the island by the century's end.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 45.</ref> In another charter, Haraldr pledged the protection of the abbey's ships and goods.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 195; [[#O2|Oliver (1861)]] pp. 77&ndash;78; [[#P4|''PoMS, H1/17/1'' (n.d.)]].</ref> His amiable interactions with the English abbey contrasted the apparent aggression of his father, who was warned by the English king not to harm the monks or their property.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 194&ndash;195.</ref> In a further charter, evidenced from a sixteenth-century copy, Haraldr confirmed his father's earlier grant of the lands of "''{{lang|la|Balhamer}}''" (probably Ballaharry), and the churches of St Ninian of "''{{lang|la|Ballacgniba}}''" and St Runius (all located in the [[List of parishes of the Isle of Man|Manx parish]] of [[Marown]]), to [[Whithorn Priory]] in [[Galloway]].<ref>[[#N1|Neville; Simpson (2012)]] p. 198 § 171; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 195&ndash;196; [[#M8|Megaw (1950)]] p. 176; [[#P7|''PoMS, H1/17/2'' (n.d.)]].</ref> Of the twenty royal charters known to have been issued by the Crovan dynasty, only three can be assigned to Haraldr's reign.<ref name="M4">[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 202.</ref>{{#tag:ref|One of the total twenty cannot be assigned to any particular ruler.<ref name="M4"/>|group=note}}

[[File:Kingdom of Mann and the Isles (Cotton MS Julius A VII, folio 46r).jpg|thumb|left|alt=Refer to caption|The name of Haraldr's realm as it appears on folio 46r of British Library Cotton MS Julius A VII (the ''[[Chronicle of Mann]]''): "''{{lang|la|regno Manniæ et Insularum}}''" ("Kingdom of Mann and the Isles").<ref>[[#B1|Broderick; Stowell (1973)]] p. 38; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 98&ndash;99; [[#C8|''Cotton MS Julius A VII'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]

Like his father before him, and his brother Magnús after him, Haraldr was [[knighted]] by Henry.<ref>[[#M2|McDonald (2015)]]; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 215, 216&ndash;217.</ref> The chronicle claims that the event took place in 1247, and elaborates that Haraldr returned home with "much honour, and great gifts".<ref>[[#M2|McDonald (2015)]]; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 215; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 84; [[#J2|Johnsen (1969)]] p. 27, 27 n. 2; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] p. 542; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 98&ndash;99.</ref> Contemporary English administrative records, however, reveal that the deed took place early in 1246. Specifically, a letter of safe-conduct, issued by the English king on 9 January 1246, orders that Haraldr was to be given safe-passage through England until [[Pentecost]] (27 May 1246).<ref>[[#M2|McDonald (2015)]]; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 215; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 84; [[#J2|Johnsen (1969)]] p. 27, 27 n. 2; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] p. 542 n. 3; [[#C1|''Calendar of the Patent Rolls...'' (1906)]] p. 469; [[#O2|Oliver (1861)]] p. 82; [[#R1|Rymer; Sanderson; Holmes (1739)]] pt. 1 p. 155; [[#D6|''Diplomatarium Norvegicum'' (n.d.)]] vol. 19 § 238.</ref> Similarly, the thirteenth-century the English chronicler [[Matthew Paris]] reported in his ''[[Chronica Majora]]'' that Henry confirmed the honour of knighthood upon Haraldr on [[Easter day]] that year.<ref>[[#M2|McDonald (2015)]]; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 163; [[#L2|Luard (1877)]] p. 551; [[#G1|Giles (1853)]] p. 168.</ref> Numerous titles were accorded to the kings of the Crovan dynasty. The style apparently preferred by Haraldr's father was ''{{lang|la|rex insularum}}''. As for Haraldr and Magnús, they appear to have favoured the variant form ''{{lang|la|rex manniae et insularum}}''.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 162; [[#M9|McLeod (2002)]] p. 28, nn. 11, 12; [[#S1|Sellar (2000)]] p. 200.</ref> According to the seventeenth-century antiquarians [[William Camden]] and [[John Selden]], this title appeared on the legend of seals borne by the dynasty.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 162; [[#H1|Harrison (1876)]] p. 7; [[#S4|Selden (1672)]] p. 24; [[#C3|Camdeno (1607)]] p. 847.</ref> It is unknown whose emblems these men were referring to, although they may well have been those of Haraldr.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 162.</ref> These titles are an equivalent of the [[Gaelic languages|Gaelic]] title ''{{lang|ghc|rí Innsi Gall}}''<ref>[[#M9|McLeod (2002)]] pp. 26&ndash;28; [[#S1|Sellar (2000)]] p. 198.</ref> ("king of the islands of the foreigners") first recorded in 989, a style almost certainly referring to Mann and the Hebrides.<ref>[[#D2|Duffy (2006)]] p. 54.</ref> Other sources accord Haraldr similar titles. The [[Icelandic annals]], for example, style him "''{{lang|non|Svðréyiakonvngs}}''" ("king of the Hebrides").<ref>[[#M9|McLeod (2002)]] p. 28; [[#S5|Storm (1977)]] p. 132; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] p. 551; [[#V3|Vigfusson (1878)]] p. 374.</ref>

==Dynastic alliance==

[[File:Haakon4.jpg|alt=Refer to caption|thumb|upright|left|[[Coat of arms]] of [[Hákon Hákonarson]] as depicted on folio 216v of Cambridge Corpus Christi College Parker Library 16II (''[[Chronica Majora]]'').<ref name="Imsen 2010 p. 13">[[#I2|Imsen (2010)]] p. 13 n. 2; [[#L1|Lewis (1987)]] p. 456; [[#T2|Tremlett; London; Wagner (1967)]] p. 72.</ref>{{#tag:ref|This coat of arms is [[blazoned]]: ''[[gules]], three galleys with dragon heads at each end [[or (heraldry)|or]], one above the other''.<ref>[[#L1|Lewis (1987)]] p. 456; [[#T2|Tremlett; London; Wagner (1967)]] p. 72.</ref> The coat of arms concerns Hákon's coronation, and its associated caption reads in Latin: "''{{lang|la|Scutum regis Norwagiae nuper coronati, qui dicitur rex Insularum}}''".<ref name="Imsen 2010 p. 13">[[#I2|Imsen (2010)]] p. 13 n. 2; [[#L1|Lewis (1987)]] p. 456; [[#T2|Tremlett; London; Wagner (1967)]] p. 72.</ref> The coat of arms was illustrated by [[Matthew Paris]], a man who met Hákon in 1248/1249, the year after the king's coronation. The emphasise that Matthew placed upon the Norwegian realm's sea power appears to be underscored in the [[heraldry]] he attributed to Hákon.<ref>[[#I2|Imsen (2010)]] pp. 13&ndash;14, 13 n. 2.</ref>|group=note}}]]

In the autumn of 1247, Haraldr again voyaged to Norway, as evidenced by the ''Chronicle of Mann'' and the thirteenth-century ''[[Hákonar saga Hákonarsonar]]''. After Haraldr removed from [[Oslo]] to [[Bergen]], these sources reveal that Hákon gave the hand of his widowed daughter, Cecilía, in marriage to Haraldr.<ref>[[#C4|Crawford (2014)]] p. 79; [[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] pp. 51&ndash;52, 78; [[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#M13|McDonald (2012)]] p. 143; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 151; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 83; [[#B6|Bandlien (2006)]] p. 228, 228 n. 144; [[#F1|Frame (1989)]] p. 148; [[#B4|Barrow (1981)]] p. 111; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 546, 547&ndash;548; [[#D3|Dasent (1894)]] pp. 264&ndash;265 (§ 259) [[#V2|Vigfusson (1887)]] pp. 254&ndash;255 (§ 259); [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 98&ndash;101.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Cecilía was one of at least two illegitimate children of Hákon. Her mother was a certain Kanga, a woman of whom nothing else is known.<ref>[[#B6|Bandlien (2006)]] p. 228.</ref> Cecilía had previously been married to a ''{{lang|non|[[lendr maðr]]}}'' named Gregorius Andrésson.<ref>[[#O5|Orfield (2002)]] p. 138.</ref>|group=note}} Throughout his long reign, Hákon endeavoured to strengthen his far-flung Norwegian realm.<ref>[[#C4|Crawford (2014)]] p. 79.</ref> In regard to the Isles, his bestowal of Cecilía in matrimony to Haraldr brought relations between the rulers of the realms to its climax.<ref>[[#C4|Crawford (2014)]] p. 79; [[#J2|Johnsen (1969)]] p. 27.</ref> The compilers of the chronicle clearly considered the union to have elevated Haraldr's prestige above that of his predecessors,<ref name="O4"/> as this source claims that Hákon had declared he would hold his new son-in-law "in great glory and exalt the throne of his kingdom above all who ruled before him in the Isles".<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 151; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] p. 546; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 100&ndash;101.</ref>

[[File:Cecilía Hákonardóttir (AM 45 fol, fol. 112v).jpg|alt=Refer to caption|thumb|right|Cecilía's name as it appears on folio 112v of AM 45 fol: "''Cecilio dottur Hakonar konvngs''".<ref>[[#U2|Unger (1871)]] p. 524; [[#A3|''AM 45 Fol'' (n.d.)]].</ref>]]

Whilst Haraldr was still in Norway, the saga states that two leading members of Clann Somhairle arrived at Hákon's court, with each seeking the kingship of the Isles: [[Eóghan of Argyll|Eóghan Mac Dubhghaill, Lord of Argyll]] and [[Dubhghall mac Ruaidhrí]].<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 83; [[#P8|Power (2005)]] p. 46; [[#B3|Brown (2004)]] p. 80; [[#S3|Sellar (2004)]]; [[#M9|McLeod (2002)]] p. 30; [[#S1|Sellar (2000)]] pp. 203&ndash;204, 206; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 547&ndash;548; [[#D3|Dasent (1894)]] pp. 264&ndash;266 (§ 259); [[#V2|Vigfusson (1887)]] pp. 254&ndash;255 (§ 259).</ref> Although 1247 was also the year of Hákon's royal coronation, and it is possible that the arrival of the Clann Somhairle dynasts was a result of the reimposition of Norwegian overlordship (as appears to have been the case with Haraldr), there may have been other reasons for the arrival of Eóghan and Dubhghall.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 83.</ref> For example, 1247 was also the year that a prominent member of Clann Somhairle, called "Mac Somhairle" in [[Irish annals|Irish sources]], was slain in Ireland battling the English.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]]; [[#S1|Sellar (2000)]] p. 201.</ref>{{#tag:ref|Various Irish sources style Mac Somhairle ''{{lang|ghc|rí Airer Goidel}}'' and ''{{lang|ghc|tigerna Airer Goidel}}''.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 165; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 77.</ref> The identity of this Clann Somhairle dynast is uncertain, although he is most likely to have been Dubhghall's father, Ruaidhrí.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#B3|Brown (2004)]] pp. 80, 81.</ref>|group=note}} The knighting of Haraldr the year previous may well have entailed some act of submission to the Henry,<ref name="O4;D7-5152;W1-8384">[[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] pp. 51&ndash;52; [[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 83&ndash;84.</ref> and it is possible that Hákon had consequently recognised Mac Somhairle's kingship in the Isles in response to Haraldr's acceptance of English overtures.<ref name="W1-8384">[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 83&ndash;84.</ref> An alliance with a ruler of the Isles would have certainly benefited Henry's ongoing military operations in Ireland,<ref>[[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] p. 56; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 83&ndash;84.</ref> and it is possible that it was such a pact that had prompted Mac Somhairle's involvement against the English.<ref name="W1-8384"/> Haraldr's subsequent marriage to Cecilía, therefore, may have been a successful attempt by Hákon to lure Haraldr back to his side.<ref name="O4;D7-5152;W1-8384"/>

==Death and after-effects==

[[File:Sumburgh Head - geograph.org.uk - 485752.jpg|alt=Photo of Sumburgh Head in the distance across a long body of water|thumb|upright|left|[[Sumburgh Head]]. Haraldr is said to have drowned nearby in [[Sumburgh Roost]], a dangerous [[tidal race]] called ''{{lang|non|Dynröst}}'' by ''Hákonar saga Hákonarsonar'', now known to Shetlanders as Da Roost.]]

In 1248, the ''Chronicle of Mann'', ''Hákonar saga Hákonarsonar'', and the Icelandic annals indicate that Haraldr and Cecilía drowned whilst voyaging from Norway to the Isles.<ref>[[#M2|McDonald (2015)]]; [[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] p. 52; [[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#M13|McDonald (2012)]] pp. 143&ndash;144; [[#W6|Wærdahl (2011)]] p. 49; [[#T1|Thomson (2008)]] p. 140; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 52, 87&ndash;88; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] p. 84; [[#P8|Power (2005)]] p. 46; [[#W5|Williams (1997)]] p. 118; [[#S5|Storm (1977)]] p. 132; [[#D9|Duncan; Brown (1956–1957)]] p. 207; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 449&ndash;550, 550 nn. 1&ndash;3, 551; [[#V3|Vigfusson (1878)]] p. 374; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 100&ndash;101.</ref> Since the wreckage of their vessel washed ashore from the south, the saga specifically states that the ship was thought to have been lost south of [[Shetland]] in ''{{lang|non|Dynröst}}'', a treacherous [[tidal race]] otherwise known in more modern times as [[Sumburgh Roost]]<ref>[[#M13|McDonald (2012)]] pp. 143&ndash;144; [[#W7|Waugh, D (2009)]] p. 112; [[#C2|Crawford (1997)]] pp. 19&ndash;20; [[#B4|Barrow (1981)]] p. 111; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 449&ndash;550, 550 nn. 1&ndash;3.</ref> and Da Roost,<ref>[[#W3|Waugh, DJ (2001)]] p. 70.</ref> lying between [[Sumburgh Head]] and [[Fair Isle]] ({{gbmapping|HU405070}}).<ref>[[#C2|Crawford (1997)]] pp. 19&ndash;20; 20 fig. 7; [[#M10|Martin; Wignall (1975)]] p. 156; [[#U1|''Unknown: Sumburgh Head'' (n.d.)]].</ref>{{#tag:ref|A nineteenth-century account of this perilous passage runs as follows: "There appears to be a strong [[Ocean current|current]] setting to the eastward in the sea between [[Orkney]] and Shetland, and in shaping a course from the main land of Scotland to Shetland some allowance ought to be made for this. Indeed, probably the best method of making the passage would he to keep the Orcadian land aboard till you reach the [[Start Point, Sanday|Start Point]] at the extremity of that Archipelago, and from thence steer a course for Sumburgh Head, keeping to the westward of the Fair Isle. The only thing to be avoided in taking this plan, is getting involved in the furious tide race, known as Sumburgh Roost: this, as we found, extends some miles to the south of the Shetland Islands, and in rough weather the sea is frightful, even in calm weather the danger is considerable, and there are instances narrated of vessels which have been {{sic|dis|masted}} in the swell, and kept vibrating backwards and forwards in these seething tides for weeks at a time. In passing the Roost you should either keep a good offing or steer close to the shore: the latter being I believe the surest method of avoiding the heavy {{sic|over|falls}}".<ref>[[#J1|JAL (1858)]] p. 66.</ref>|group=note}} Amongst those drowned was [[Laurence, Archdeacon of Mann]], a man who had recently been elected [[Bishop of the Isles]] by the chapter of Mann. Although Laurence had presented himself in Norway to Haraldr and [[Sigurðr tapsi Indriðason|Sigurðr tapsi Indriðason, Archbishop of Niðaróss]], the chronicle reveals that Haraldr had postponed his consecration until the former could be publicly elected in the Isles before king, clergy, and people.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#W2|Woolf (2003)]] p. 178; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 546&ndash;547; [[#D4|Dowden (1912)]] p. 278; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 100&ndash;101.</ref>

{{multiple image
| direction = vertical
| footer    = Nineteenth-century representations of seventeenth-century illustrations of Haraldr's now non-existent [[Seal (emblem)|seals]].<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 55&ndash;56 n. 78; [[#O3|Oswald (1860)]] frontispiece.</ref>
| width     = 170
| image1    = Harald Olafsson, King of Mann and the Isles (seal 01).jpg
| alt1      = Refer to caption
| image2    = Harald Olafsson, King of Mann and the Isles (seal 02).jpg
| alt2      = Refer to caption
}}

Haraldr's death led to what was the final stage of inter-dynastic strife amongst his family.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 87&ndash;88, 90.</ref> News of Haraldr and Cecilía's death does not appear to have reached Mann until the spring of 1249.<ref name="O4"/> According to the chronicle, Haraldr's younger brother, Rǫgnvaldr, succeeded to the kingship on 6 May 1249, only to be slain on 30 May by a man who appears to have been an accomplice of Rǫgnvaldr and Haraldr's cousin, Haraldr Guðrøðarson. With Rǫgnvaldr out of the way, Haraldr Guðrøðarson successfully seized the throne, and replaced Haraldr's former supporters with proponents of his own.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] pp. 87&ndash;88, 96; [[#W5|Williams (1997)]] p. 260; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 550, 553&ndash;554; 557&ndash;558; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 100&ndash;103.</ref> According to the chronicle, one of the men who suffered under Haraldr Guðrøðarson's regime was a certain chieftain called "''{{lang|la|Dofnaldus}}''". This man is stated to have been held in high esteem by Haraldr, but held a prisoner by Haraldr Guðrøðarson.<ref>[[#M4|McDonald (2007b)]] p. 99; [[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 78&ndash;82; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 566&ndash;567; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 102&ndash;105.</ref> Although the identity of this man is uncertain, he could be identical to Domhnall, the eponym of [[Clann Domhnaill]]. If such an identification is correct, and if Haraldr's mother was indeed Lauon of Clann Somhairle, the captive Dofnaldus would have been a close kinsman of Haraldr (perhaps a maternal uncle or maternal grandfather). In fact, Haraldr seems to have relied upon Hebridean support as opposed to Manx support during his reign.<ref>[[#W1|Woolf (2007)]] pp. 78&ndash;82.</ref> For example, the chronicle makes note of three sons of a certain Niall who supported Haraldr's cause early in his reign.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 507&ndash;509; [[#M11|Munch; Goss (1874)]] pp. 94&ndash;97.</ref> It is possible that these men were related to a certain Domhnall mac Néill,<ref name="O4"/> an obscure figure who faced the brunt of a Scottish royal army in 1221. The latter's patronym suggests that he may have had Hebridean<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#O6|Oram (2005)]] pp. 36&ndash;37.</ref> or [[Ulster]] connections.<ref>[[#O6|Oram (2005)]] pp. 36&ndash;37.</ref>

[[File:Alexander II, King of Scotland, coat of arms (Royal MS 14 C VII, 146v).jpg|alt=Refer to caption|upright|left|thumb|Coat of arms of Alexander as it appears on folio 146v of British Library Royal MS 14 C VII (''[[Historia Anglorum (Matthew Paris)|Historia Anglorum]]'').<ref>[[#L1|Lewis (1987)]] pp. 466, 497 n. 185; [[#R4|''Royal MS 14 C VII'' (n.d.)]].</ref> The inverted shield represents the king's death in 1249.<ref>[[#L1|Lewis (1987)]] p. 497 n. 185.</ref>{{#tag:ref|This coat of arms is blazoned: ''or, a [[lion rampant]] gules and a [[bordure]] flory counter gules''.<ref>[[#L1|Lewis (1987)]] p. 466.</ref>|group=note}}]]

The maritime disaster in which Haraldr and Cecilía lost their lives demonstrates some of the difficulties faced by the [[King of Norway|Norwegian Crown]] in maintaining control of the far-flung Norse colonies west over sea.<ref name="Barrow 1981 p. 111"/>{{#tag:ref|The term "west over sea", used in saga-literature, denotes the relative direction of [[Great Britain|Britain]] and [[Ireland]] in relation to Norway.|group=note}} Not only did the calamity deprive the Islesmen of a capable king, but cost the Norwegian Crown a closely connected advocate in the region.<ref name="O4"/> Upon learning of the catastrophe, Hákon quickly sent Eóghan west over sea to temporarily take up the kingship of the Isles on his behalf.<ref>[[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] p. 52; [[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#S3|Sellar (2004)]]; [[#C6|Carpenter (2003)]] ch. 10; [[#S1|Sellar (2000)]] p. 204.</ref> Eóghan, however, was not only a Norwegian dependant in the Isles, but an immanent Scottish [[magnate]] on the mainland.<ref name="O4;S3;C6-6">[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#S3|Sellar (2004)]].</ref> For several years the [[King of Scotland|Scottish Crown]] appears to have attempted to acquire the Hebrides from Norwegian overlordsip, and expand its authority in [[Argyll]].<ref>[[#D7|Dahlberg (2014)]] pp. 52&ndash;54; [[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#B3|Brown (2004)]] p. 80; [[#C6|Carpenter (2003)]] ch. 10; [[#B4|Barrow (1981)]] p. 115.</ref> The apparent cooling of relations between Eóghan and Alexander,<ref name="O4"/> along with Haraldr's later demise,<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#B3|Brown (2004)]] p. 80; [[#T1|Thomson (2008)]] p. 140; [[#B4|Barrow (1981)]] p. 111.</ref> the resulting kin-strife concerning his succession,<ref>[[#B3|Brown (2004)]] p. 80.</ref> and Eóghan's subsequent acceptance of royal powers on Hákon's behalf, could all have contributed to the massed invasion into Argyll by Scottish royal forces within the year.<ref name="O4;S3;C6-6"/> After Alexander demanded Eóghan renounce his allegiance to Hákon, and ordered him to hand over certain mainland and island fortresses, Eóghan apparently withdrew into the northern Hebrides. The unfolding crisis only ended with the Scottish king's untimely death soon afterwards in July.<ref>[[#O4|Oram (2013)]]; [[#P8|Power (2005)]] p. 47; [[#B3|Brown (2004)]] p. 80; [[#S3|Sellar (2004)]]; [[#T1|Thomson (2008)]] p. 140; [[#B4|Barrow (1981)]] pp. 115&ndash;116.</ref> According to ''Hákonar saga Hákonarsonar'', Alexander had made it clear that he had no intention of turning back until he had acquired control of the western Norwegian dominions within his sights.<ref>[[#C6|Carpenter (2003)]] ch. 10; [[#A2|Anderson (1922)]] pp. 555; [[#D3|Dasent (1894)]] p. 265 (§ 265) [[#V2|Vigfusson (1887)]] pp. 259&ndash;260 (§ 265).</ref> Within about two decades, such desires would be fully realised by his [[Alexander III of Scotland|successor-son]], with the final eclipse of Norwegian overlordship in the Isles and the extinction of the Crovan dynasty itself.<ref>[[#C6|Carpenter (2003)]] ch. 12.</ref>

