{{about|the New Zealand hospital|the hospital in New York|Northwell Health|the hospital in Australia|Royal North Shore Hospital}} {{Infobox hospital | Name = North Shore Hospital | Org/Group = <!-- optional --> | Image = North Shore Hospital across Lake Pupuke.jpg | Caption = View of North Shore Hospital across the adjacent [[Lake Pupuke]] | Size = 180px | Logo = <!-- optional --> | Location = [[North Shore City|North Shore]] | Region = Auckland | State = | Country = New Zealand | HealthCare = Waitemata District Health Board | Type = Teaching, specialist | Speciality = [[Tertiary Hospital]] | Standards = <!-- optional --> | Emergency = Yes | Affiliation= <!-- unknown to me --> | Beds = 600+ | Founded = 1958 as a maternity hospital, 1984 as tertiary hospital | Closed = <!-- optional --> | Website = http://www.waitematadhb.govt.nz/ | Wiki-Links = <!-- optional --> |}}
'''North Shore Hospital''' is a large [[public hospital]] in [[Takapuna]], New Zealand, serving the northern part of [[Auckland]]. Located on Shakespeare Road near [[Lake Pupuke]], it is administered by the Waitemata [[District Health Board]], which provides health services to approximately 600,000 residents of the North Shore, Waitakere and Rodney districts of Auckland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.health.govt.nz/new-zealand-health-system/my-dhb/waitemata-dhb|title=Waitemata DHB - Ministry of Health NZ |accessdate=7 Aug 2018}}</ref> [[Emergency Department]] staff at North Shore see more than 60,000 cases each year.{{cn|date=October 2017}}
==Facilities== The hospital provides up to 600 [[surgery|surgical]] and general medical treatment beds. It has twelve [[operating theatre]]s (one specialised in [[Obstetrics|obstetric]] care), an emergency department, a 50-bed Assessment and Diagnostic Unit, an [[Intensive care medicine|intensive care]] centre, an Elective Surgery Centre and a [[Cardiology|coronary care]], as well as a [[maternity]] and [[Neonatal Intensive Care Unit|special care baby unit]].<ref name="NSH"/>
The hospital also provides [[endoscope|endoscopy]], [[radiology]], [[pathology]], [[anaesthetic]], [[gynecological]], general surgery, a cardiac catheter lab and [[mental health]] services through the onsite Marinoto and He Puna Waiora units. Visiting specialists cover a number of further medical sub-disciplines. Two of the wards specialise in assessment, treatment and [[Physical medicine and rehabilitation|rehabilitation]] of [[Old age|older patients]] over 65 years of age.<ref name="NSH">[http://www.healthpoint.co.nz/default,51123.sm North Shore Hospital] (database entry on healthpoint.co.nz website. Accessed 2008-06-21.)</ref>
==Funding and staffing== In 2007, North Shore Hospital repeatedly reported 100% occupancy rates and difficulties in finding enough staff. This is alleged to be partly due to North Shore City's affluence, with the catchment area having some of the highest average incomes in New Zealand, as well as scoring high on other social indicators. As the District Health Board funding scheme distributes money based on these indicators, it has been claimed that it receives much less funding per population served than hospitals in other areas of the country.<ref name="NZ_Herald_10450352">{{cite news |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/hospitals/news/article.cfm?c_id=500846&objectid=10450352 |title=Editorial: Hospital funding not fair |date=9 July 2007 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=1 November 2011}}</ref>
The issues with staff shortages and overcrowding, repeatedly discussed in the press during the middle of 2007, have led two North Shore [[National Party of New Zealand|National]] MPs to inquire into the issue, noting that a 'crisis of confidence' had developed, which was generating more concern from locals 'than anything else in recent times'.<ref>''Hospital worries'' - ''[[The New Zealand Herald]]'', Thursday 12 July 2007</ref>
In 2011 North Shore Hospital opened an Assessment and Diagnostic Unit (ADU) designed to improve overcrowding and patient flow through the North Shore Emergency Department, and increase inpatient bed capacity. [[Waitemata DHB]] has since made improvements against the NZ Ministry of Health's Shorter Stays in ED target.<ref>http://www.stuff.co.nz/auckland/local-news/north-shore-times/6771819/Hospital-bounces-back-from-troubles</ref> From July to September 2009 61% of patients were admitted, discharged or transferred from an emergency department within six hours. For the same period in 2013, 95% of patients were admitted, discharged or transferred within six hours.<ref>http://www.health.govt.nz/new-zealand-health-system/health-targets/how-my-dhb-performing</ref>
